Major refactor to improve speed on difficut images, especially when running a heap checker. SEAM and SPLIT have been begging for a refactor for a *LONG* time. This change does most of the work of turning them into proper classes:   Moved relevant code into SEAM/SPLIT/TBLOB/EDGEPT etc from global helper functions.   Made the splits full data members of SEAM in an array instead of 3 separate pointers. This greatly reduces the amount of new/delete happening in the chopper, which is the main goal.   Deleted redundant files: olutil.*,  makechop.*   Brought other code into SEAM in order to keep its data members private with only priority having accessors.
Makefile.am change for Split/seam refactor

Fixed issue 1252: Refactored LearnBlob and its call hierarchy to make it a member of Classify. Eliminated the flexfx scheme for calling global feature extractor functions through an array of function pointers. Deleted dead code I found as a by-product. This CL does not change BlobToTrainingSample or ExtractFeatures to be full members of Classify (the eventual goal) as that would make it even bigger, since there are a lot of callers to these functions. When ExtractFeatures and BlobToTrainingSample are members of Classify they will be able to access control parameters in Classify, which will greatly simplify developing variations to the feature extraction process.
Makefile.am for fix to issue 1252
Add ability to build under android (without cube or scrollview).
Fixed problems with shifted baselines so recognition can recover from layout analysis errors.

Major change to improve layout analysis for heavily diacritic languages: Tha, Vie, Kan, Tel etc. There is a new overlap detector that detects when diacritics cause a big increase in textline overlap. In such cases, diacritics from overlap regions are kept separate from layout analysis completely, allowing textline formation to happen without them. The diacritics are then assigned to 0, 1 or 2 close words at the end of layout analysis, using and modifying an old noise detection data path. The stored diacritics are used or not during recognition according to the character classifier's liking for them.

Font and classifier output structure cleanup. Font recognition was poor, due to forcing a 1st and 2nd choice at a character level, when the total score for the correct font is often correct at the word level, so allowed the propagation of a full set of fonts and scores to the word recognizer, which can now decide word level fonts using the scores instead of simple votes.Change precipitated a cleanup of output data structures for classifiernresults, eliminating ScoredClass and INT_RESULT_STRUCT, with a fewnextra elements going in UnicharRating, and using that wherever possible.nThat added the extra complexity of 1-rating due to a flip between 0 isngood and 0 is bad for the internal classifier scores before they arenconverted to rating and certainty.n
Changes missed from diacritic fix edit

Significant change to invisible font system to improve correctness and compatibility with external programs, particularly ghostscript. We will start mapping everything to a single glyph, rather than allowing characters to run off the end of the font.A more detailed design discussion is embedded intonpdfrenderer.cpp comments. The font, source codenthat produces the font, and the design commentsnwere contributed by Ken Sharp from Artifex Software.n

Issue 1351: OpenCL build - kernel_ThresholdRectToPix() not accounting for padding bits in the output pix?!https://code.google.com/p/tesseract-ocr/issues/detail?id=1351nnWhat steps will reproduce the problem?n1.Use tesseract build with OpenCL.n2.Pass full color image with width which is not multiple of 32.n3.Recognition is way too slow and does not recognize anything.nI read the article on http://www.sk-spell.sk.cx/tesseract-meets-the-opencl-first-test and decided to give OCL a try. The initial result was as per point 3 above. After some debugging I figured the problem is that the OCL version of threshold rect generation does not account for padding bits in the output pix lines. To prove my discovery I made a quick fix in oclkernels.h replacing the definition of kernel_ThresholdRectToPixnnJust a reminder: it is necessary to force OCL kernel recompilation after changing this source (e.g. delete u00e2u0080u009ckernel - <device>.binu00e2u0080u009d from the exec folder).nThe fix is working but I am not sure about it since the original source apparently works for other people (as per the article). If I am right the OS/GPU are irrelevant since the bug is algorithmic, but mine are Windows/AMD. Also similar fix is applicable to kernel_ThresholdRectToPix_OneChan(), but there the input array might have some padding bytes as well, so its indexing will need further adjustments. I can come with some prove/fix for it either - I have not played with it yet.nDisclaimer: I have no prior experience with image processing and tesseract source or with GPU computing and OpenCL (but please do explain if I am wrong).n

tesstrain.sh: Only fall back to default Latin fonts if none were providedThe --fontlist argument to tesstrain.sh was always ignored, even ifnthe language had no specific fonts specified in language-specific.sh.nnChange this behaviour so the --fontlist argument is used if no specifcnfonts are selected by language-specific.sh.n

tesstrain.sh: Only set FONTS if they weren't set on the command linePreviously the fonts specified in language-selection.sh would overridenany specified on the command line.nnThis changes language-specific.sh from overriding a user request tonjust setting the default fonts if none are specified with --fontlist.n

tesstrain.sh: Initialise fontconfig even if Arial isn't availableThe fontconfig initialisation hardcodes using Arial. However it maynnot be available, whereas the fonts being used later will be, so usenone of them for initialisation instead.n

Remove --bin_dir option from tesstrain.sh (should use $PATH instead)The --bin_dir option to tesstrain.sh is not useful, as $PATH does thensame job much better, so switch to relying on that instead.nnThis also makes the code a bit more readable, as it removes the neednto refer to binaries as COMMAND_NAME_EXE rather than just command_name.n

Enable all ligatures available in a font for text2image renderingThis enables all OpenType ligatures for a specific font, wherenavailable. Specifically, it explicitly enables the OpenTypenfeatures liga (standard ligatures), hlig (historical ligatures),nclig (contextual ligatures), and dlig (discretionary ligatures).nnThis feature requires Pango 1.38 or newer.n

Only enable extra ligatures with recent Pango versionsPango's opentype feature selection functions are only availablenfrom version 1.38+, which is still quite new, so ensure it's justnignored if using an older version.n

Implement a new orientation and script detection API for C and C++See issue #424.nnThe existing C API for TessBaseAPIDetectOS requires a C caller to successfully allocate struct OSResults which is actually a C++ class.  Generally it won'tnbe possible for a regular C compiler to do this properly.nnIt's also assumed that most API level users of Tesseract are only interested in Tesseract's best guess as to script and orientation, not the individual values for all possible scripts.nnThis introduces a new API with a better name that is more closely aligned with the output of 'tesseract -psm 0'.  Both tesseract -psm 0 and this API now share the same code in baseapi.cpp.n

Add a context-aware progress monitor pointerThe progress_callback field in the ETEXT_DESC monitor type does notntake any 'context' parameter, which may make implementing callbacknfunctions difficult and may require use of global variables.nThe new function receives the ETEXT_DESC pointer as an argument.nThis makes it possible to share the cancel_this field as contextncarrier if required.nThe change is backwards-compatible: the old pointer remains as anmember of the class, and the default value for the new pointer isna function calling the classic progress notifier. This way the codenunaware of the new member will continue to work as before.n

Add progress monitoring C apiThe C API is missing the ability to monitor the progress of thenrecognition. This patch adds C wrappers to the progress monitornthat allow monitoring the progress and canceling the recognitionnprocess early.n
Fixed a typo in the C API progress monitor

Return a value from default progress report functionThe progress reporting function returns a boolean. The returnednvalue is never used by the tesseract and its meaing is notndocumented, which renders the value meaningless. Still, lack ofnreturn should not be premitted.n

Fixed Invalid F spec error while building FullyConnected layer.`int depth = strtol(*str + 1, str, 10);`rn`**str` holds the words in the VGSL specification, and `*str` holds a single word, lets say, `Fr64`. Now, the `strtol` function modifies `str` to point to the first character which a non-digit number, and assumes that ` *str+1 ` points to a number (of valid integer format) as a string (automatically skipping all the white spaces, and no other characters), where in reality, it seems to point to `r` in `Fr164`.This is a bad argument, which results in strtol returning 0.rn` strtol (*str + 2, str, 10)` should be passed instead.

Don't set page segmentation mode for hocr, pdf and tsv configsSetting the page segmentation mode in those config files gives unexpectednresults: the text recognized when no config or only txt is given changesnif both txt and any of hocr, pdf or tsv is chosen.nnIn a test set of nearly 200 pages from historical books, usingnsegmentation mode 1 is typically slightly better than the default,nbut there are also cases where it is much worse. Therefore the usernshould be able to decide which page segmentation mode is best.nnOld results for hocr, pdf or tsv now need an explicit `--psm 1` fornreproduction.nnSigned-off-by: Stefan Weil <sw@weilnetz.de>n

Allow orientation detection with any traineddataWhile orientation and script detection (OSD) normally requiresnosd.traineddata to detect both, it must also be possible to dononly orientation detection with eng.traineddata or any otherntraineddata.nnEnforce osd.traineddata only if there was no `-l` command line option.nnCommit 27ce472666a6332f38888cd6855e1162fb82c729 was too restrictive.nnSigned-off-by: Stefan Weil <sw@weilnetz.de>n

Don't set page segmentation mode for unlv configSetting the page segmentation mode to 6 (Assume a single uniform blocknof text) typically improves the layout detection for such texts, butnshould not be done in the config file.nnunlvtests/runtestset.sh adds `--psm 6` explicitly, so test resultsnwon't change when using that script.nnThis is similar to commit ecfee53bac59e5467f8a8fb5026928a1d39b5c6d.nnSigned-off-by: Stefan Weil <sw@weilnetz.de>n

Always use isascii() with isspace()isspace() must only used with an unsigned char or EOF argument,nand even then its result can depend on the current locale settings.nnWhile this is not a problem for C/C++ executables which use the defaultnC locale, it becomes a problem when the Tesseract API is called fromnlanguages like Python or Java which don't use the C locale.nnBy calling isasci() before calling isspace() this uncertainty can benavoided, because any locale will hopefully give identical results fornthe basic ASCII character set.nnSigned-off-by: Stefan Weil <sw@weilnetz.de>n

Pythonize tesstrain.sh -> tesstrain.pyThis is a lightweight, semi-Pythonic conversion of tesstrain.sh that currentlynsupports only LSTM and not the Tesseract 3 training mode.nnI attempted to keep source changes minimal so it would be easy to comparenbash to Python in code review and confirm equivalence.nnPython 3.6+ is required.  Ubuntu 18.04 ships Python 3.6 and it is a mandatorynpackage (the package manager is also written in Python), so it is availablenin the baseline Tesseract 4.0 system.nnThere are minor output and behavioral changes, and advantages.  Python's loggingis used.  Temporary files are only deleted on success, so they can be inspectednif training files.  Console output is more terse and the log file is morenverbose.  And there are progress bars!  (The python3-tqdm package is required.)nWhere tesstrain.sh would sometimes fail without explanation and return an errorncode of 1, it is much easier to find the point of failure in this version.nThat was also the main motivation for this work.nnArgument checking is also more comprehensive.n
Autoreformat codeThis increases the deviation from the bash scripts so is done separately.n
Fix some of Codacy's complaints

pango_font_info: Fix runtime error messages from Pangopango_coverage_get and pango_coverage_unref should not be callednwith coverage == nullptr.nnpango_font_get_coverage should not be called with font == nullptr.nnOtherwise Pango prints runtime error messages:nn(process:12657): Pango-CRITICAL **: pango_coverage_get: assertion 'coverage != NULL' failedn(process:12657): Pango-CRITICAL **: pango_coverage_unref: assertion 'coverage != NULL' failedn(process:12657): Pango-CRITICAL **: pango_font_get_coverage: assertion 'font != NULL' failedn(process:12657): GLib-GObject-CRITICAL **: g_object_unref: assertion 'G_IS_OBJECT (object)' failednnTypically those errors occur if a required font is not installed,nso this can be a quite common error.nnFix also a potential resource leak in PangoFontInfo::CoversUTF8Text.nnSigned-off-by: Stefan Weil <sw@weilnetz.de>n

training: Don't terminate after processing 8 fonts or 8 imagestesstrain_utils.sh sets the shell flag -e, so it exits immediatelynif a command exits with a non-zero status.nnThe following command returns a non-zero status as soon as counter is anmultiple of par_factor (par_factor=8, that means as soon as 8 fonts ornimages are processed):nnlet rem=counter%par_factornnThe new code fixes this undesired exit.nnSigned-off-by: Stefan Weil <sw@weilnetz.de>n

Fix text2image compilation on C++17 compilersC++17 drops support for `std::random_shuffle`, breaking C++17 compilersnthat run to compile text2image.cpp. std::shuffle is valid on C++11nthrough C++17, so use std::shuffle instead.nnDue to the use `std::random_shuffle`, `text2image --render_ngrams`nwould not give consistent results for different compilers or platforms.nWith the current change, the same random number generator is used fornall platforms and initialized to the same seed, so training outputnshould be consistent.n

Exposed the text2image option --ptsize to tesstrain.sh.  Text2image has the option --ptsize which defaults to 12.  This option is not exposed through tesstrain.sh; thus, you cannot use tesstrain.sh to explore training with different font sizes.  I made a small modification to expose the --ptsize option to tesstrain.sh.  It defaults to 12 if not specified.
